It appears from contemporary records7 that, in the month of August 1588, Sir William Stewart, eommanding the royal guard of Scothmd, was sent to Denmark to arrange the preli- minaries of King James's marriage, and that he returned to Edinburgh upon the l5th of November 1588. There can be no doubt that the volume above-mentioned is that referred to in Craig’s epistle to Tycho. Neither can it be doubted that this was Dr John Craig‚ third son of Sir Thomas Craig of Riecartom and physician to J ames VI. He was raised to his highest post in the royal household by a gift from that monarch, recorded in the Foedera, ‘4 dilecto nobis J ohanni Craigio in medicinis doctori, officium et locum ordinarii, et primarii medici nostriss’ dated at VVestminsten 20th June, 1603. Thjs was the friend of Tyeho Brahe and of Napier. The Danish astronomer transmitted his present to John Craig, from his palace of Uraniburg, with the air of the Monarch of Seience.
